"/> Actually, I doubt it makes a bit of difference to the underwriter
whether they insure groups or individuals. The Law of Large Numbers
works the same, whether you insure 100 groups of 5000 people or
500,000 individuals. In either case the insurer can expect to pay out
$somuch per person per year, based on past experience, so they need to
charge $somuch + something for their overhead and profit.

The one area where insuring a group is &quot;better&quot; is in the cost of
_selling_ the insurance. If you insure 500,000 individuals, you have
to sell the idea of health insurance _and_ that they should choose
_your_ insurance instead of one of your competitors, 500,000 times.
If you insure 100 groups, you only have to sell it 500 times.

The one thing that _does_ matter in a group is that everybody in the
group is covered (and pays premiums or has premiums paid on their
behalf). Otherwise you get the effect called &quot;adverse selection&quot;.
What that means is that people will wait, buying no health insurance
or only minimal insurance, until they get sick. Then they will buy
insurance at the group rate, and you end up insuring just those people
who are going to cost you the most. If insurance is mandatory for the
group (as with people working for a large employer)(*), then the
insurer can charge a &quot;reasonable&quot; premium for the whole group, which
includes both the young (mostly healthy) and the older workers (who
are more likely to have chronic problems that raise the cost of
insuring them.

(*) Most employers will let you opt out if somebody else in your
family has employer-paid health insurance that covers you, but not if
you are buying individual insurance. Again, it's because otherwise
the youngest &amp; healthiest would buy individual insurance and take
advantage of the lower premiums.

Note that this problem doesn't occur with individual health insurance.
When you apply for insurance, they require a medical exam and
permission to go through your medical records. So they know if you're
healthy, and if not, what problems you have that are likely to cost
more than the population average. Then they adjust your premium
accordingly.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;&gt;Is this a good way to go about things, or would it be better to keep
&gt;&gt;health insurance out of the office?

&gt;What's the proposed alternative? Have everybody buy individual
&gt;policies? Have group policies based on some grouping other than
&gt;employer (and, if so, what?) Single-payer like Canada?

"/> One reason why &quot;employer-paid&quot; health insurance is so popular is
because it's tax deductible. My employer gets to count what they pay
as a business expense -- which lowers their taxes. But the (indirect)
payment to me of them covering my health insurance isn't taxable
income for me -- or for anybody (except the insurance company, to the
extent it makes a profit it can't hide from the taxman). What a great
deal.

Note that this type of insurance is mostly provided to people like me
who make above-average salaries. If you work at a minimum-wage job,
you don't get health insurance. Makes sense, the tax benefit isn't as
big at $15,000/year as it is when you make over $80K.

Which means of course that all the people working for Wal-Mart and
McDs and such like jobs are in effect _subsidizing me_ and people like
me -- I get a benefit that they don't, and I don't pay taxes on it.
But if they want to buy health insurance, they pay for it with dollars
that they have already paid taxes on!

This doesn't strike me as equitable somehow...

One &quot;solution&quot; is to make health insurance a taxable benefit, just as
life insurance (over $50K) is. Then there would be less demand for
this &quot;benefit&quot; from those of us in the upper-income scale. And with
fewer people going to doctors and not much caring how much it costs
because somebody else is paying the bill, there would be more
incentive for doctors, hospitals, and drug companies to keep costs and
prices down. Right now, the two most important things about a doctor
(or hospital) to me are

1) Do they have a track record (with me or other people I know)
that convinces me they will probably take good care of me --
cure whatever ails me, or alleviate it as much as possible if
it can't be cured.
2) How much _time_ do they cost me. A doctor close to work is
favored over one further away, and one who is usually on time
is &quot;better&quot; than one who is habitually late. Why? Because if
I spend more than 40 hours away during the workday in a year, I
will lose vacation days or possibly even wages.

Meanwhile, those who make less money don't go to the doctor until they
get sick enough they can't function, because they can't afford the
co-payments (if they have insurance) or the fees (if they don't).

Again this doesn't seem right.
