"/> The problem has nothing to do with group insurance per se. The problem
is that employers do not buy insurance with a &quot;guaranteed for life
renewable/convertible&quot; even though that just saves them 5% on premiums.
The &quot;guaranteed renewable/convertible&quot; feature means you can continue to
buy insurance at the original groups rates even if you are no longer
employed and your health fails and you become otherwise uninsurable. All
individual policies have this feature since it does not make sense for
the insured not to demand this feature for just 5% extra, but the
employer doesn't care what happens to the insured after he/she is no
longer employed, so choses to save 5% by excluding &quot;guaranteed
renewability/convertibility&quot;.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="

&gt;&gt;Is this a good way to go about things, or would it be better to keep
&gt;&gt;health insurance out of the office?

&gt;What's the proposed alternative? Have everybody buy individual
&gt;policies? Have group policies based on some grouping other than
&gt;employer (and, if so, what?) Single-payer like Canada?

"/> There is a simple solution : US Congress should pass a law requiring all
employers to offer &quot;guaranteed renewable/convertible&quot; health insurance.
It would be OK if employers were allowed to pass on the extra 5% cost to
the employee and make it optional (only an idiot employee would chose
not to pay the extra 5%).

Some Congressmen have tried to do this in the past by extending the
right to continue coverage after employment ends from 1.5 years to life
(as now the employee would pay the premium after employment ends, but it
could be no more than 102% of what it costs fior existing employees)
This would effectively force employers to buy &quot;guaranteed
renewable/convertible&quot; health insurance (or take on the risk of
ex-employees with poor health themselves). Instead a watered down
version fo the bill was passed : At the request of insurance industry
it now merely entitles formerly covered employees after their COBRA
coverage of 1.5 years expires, to buy any individual health policy
without having to pay a &quot;pre-existing condition&quot; premium surcharge,
provided the new policy is bought within 60 days of the old policy
lapsing. The new insurance company can recover the cost of pre-existing
conditions from the previous employer's insurance company, I believe.

Note for those savvy enough to buy their own individual policy after
losing covered employment for more than 1.5 years you effectively have
&quot;guaranteed renewable/convertible&quot; health insurance. The limitation of
the current law is primarilty that it forces former employees after 1.5
years to buy individual policies that are more expensive and more
lucrative for the insurance industry.

