"/> Medical costs are often fairly predictable based on past medical history.
That kind of defeats the purpose of insurance (imagine if someone were to
buy minimal or no medical insurance, then got a diagnosis of some expensive
medical problem, then bought higher coverage medical insurance before getting
the expensive treatment).

Employer groups are used because most people choose employment on the
basis of things other than medical insurance (at least when considering
employers that offer medical insurance to employees), so the risk
spreading function of insurance works somewhat better than with
individually bought medical insurance.

Obviously, there are plenty of problems with employer group medical
insurance (versus other schemes of buying medical insurance):

1. Changing jobs means changing medical insurance.

2. Users and buyers may have different priorities when choosing the level
or type of insurance versus the premiums it costs.

3. Self employed, retired, student, unemployed, etc. people do not fit
into the employer group scheme. Also, small businesses may find it
more difficult or expensive to buy medical insurance for their employees
than large businesses.

4. Medical insurance adds an overhead to the cost of employing someone,
although the employee may not gain the full value of the cost of the
insurance (because s/he would have preferred different medical insurance).

