"/> Believe it or not, the extra 2.7% (or perhaps more) is people crossing
the border into the US to buy healthcare in our (partly private)
market.

But the last figure I saw for the US was closer to 14% of GDP spent on
healthcare. But you have to be careful when you compare spending.
Frinstance, I suspect that the 9% GDP for Canada counts direct
spending (hospital and medical bills) but not indirect spending
(travel costs and cost of lodgings in the US while being treated).

Also to be considered is the quality of what you are getting. This
varies _extremely_ widely in the US. If you are able to get (and
afford) an &quot;indemnity&quot; plan(*), you can get very good care *if* you
are careful about choosing your physician. If you choose an
overworked or careless or otherwise not-very-good doctor, you can get
mediocre care (or worse) while paying premium prices. But with an
&quot;indemnity&quot; or PPO plan, you can almost always be treated within a day
or two for most conditions. Or at least get the process started with
appropriate tests, etc. This applies to people on traditional
Medicare, with or without a supplemental plan (A through H depending
on what you want covered).

(*) One where you choose your doctor and the insurance pays the bills,
up to some maximum that they determine by a survey of charges for a
given condition/procedure in your area.

If you have to rely on an HMO (including Medicare patients who have
chosen a medicare HMO plan to save money), you can wait almost as long
here as you would in Canada. In fact, with an HMO you may be denied
treatment for a life threatening condition, because the &quot;gatekeeper&quot;
doesn't want to spend the money for the test to see what's wrong with
you. If you have an employer-paid HMO plan, you won't even be able to
sue for the loss of your life or limb or whatever -- just for what
they would have paid if they had covered the treatment. Needless to
say, this doesn't give HMOs much incentive to treat people right when
they get an expensive illness. (HMOs _do_ have an incentive to treat
people with common illlenesses well, because the word gets around and
their customers can &quot;vote with their feet&quot;. Most employers offer a
choice of plans and people can switch pretty freely once a year.)

But as somebody else noted, employer-paid plans are health-care plans,
not health &quot;insurance&quot;. They pay for routine care including annual
physicals. And if you have something catastrophic go wrong, you may
have trouble getting approval for treatment, esp. in an HMO. WHich is
the exact opposite of true insurance. Insurance is supposed to
protect you from _catastrophic_ events -- like that brain tumor that
requires $50K of surgery and may need another $100K of followup, or a
multi-$100K heart transplant.

But with true insurance you would pay your &quot;normal&quot; expenses out of
your own pocket. That includes not only routine stuff like physical
exams, but also the average $1000 or $2000 that almost everybody
spends on medical treatment every year. And in fact it should have
a deductible somewhat bigger than your typical year's expenses. If
your average expenses are $1000, then you should probably carry a
deductible of $2000 or so. You should just have enough liquid assets
to cover an _occasional_ event that approximately doubles _one_
element of your normal yearly expenses. If you can't, you are
living beyond your means. In fact, anybody who has been working more
than about 5-7 years should have an extra full year of living expenses
in the bank or some other place where you can easily get at it.

Always remember: TANSTAAFL. There Ain't No Such Thing As A Free
Lunch. And there ain't no such thing as free medical care. If we
choose to pay for medical care for everybody, we're going to have to
give up something else that we like. Maybe spend less on the
military, or on support for the aged (Social Security), or maybe pay
higher taxes.

Oh, and btw in case you haven't been paying attention to election
results, higher taxes aren't real popular with the people who vote.
